        "text": "As it is certain that Jesus cannot have predicted His resurrection in any explicit or intelligible manner even to His own disciples; as, moreover, it is impossible to suppose that the women who visited the grave on the resurrection morning could have contemplated embalming the body, or would have concerned themselves merely about how the stone was to be rolled away, if they had been aware that a watch had been set, and that the grave had been sealed; and finally, as the supposition that Pilate complied with the request for a guard, or at all events, that the members of the Sanhedrim so little understood their own interest as both to leave the body of Jesus in the hands of His followers instead of taking possession of it themselves, and to bribe the soldiers to give false testimony instead of duly calling them to account, as they might have done, for their culpable neglect, is in the highest degree improbable, just as much so as the idea that the procurator would be likely to take no notice of a dereliction of duty on the part of his own soldiers, who, by maintaining the truth of a very stupid fabrication, would only be proclaiming how much they themselves were to blame in the matter: it follows that the story about the watching of the grave—a story which is further disproved by the fact that nowhere in the discussions belonging to the apostolic age do we find any reference ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "confirmatory",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "otherwise",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to the alleged stealing of the body—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "must be referred to the category of unhistorical legend",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". And a clue to the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "origin",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of this legend is furnished by the evangelist himself in mentioning the rumour about the stealing of the body,—a rumour emanating to all appearance from a Jewish source, and circulated with the hostile intention of disproving the resurrection of Jesus (Paulus, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "exeg. Handb",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". III. p. 837 ff.; Strauss, II. p. 562 ff.; Schleiermacher, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "L. J",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". p. 458 ff.; Weisse, Ewald, Hase, Bleek, Keim, Scholten, Hilgenfeld). The arguments advanced by Hug in the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Freyburg. Zeitschr",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". 1831, 3, p. 184 ff.; 5, p. 80 ff.; Kuinoel, Hofmann, Krabbe, Ebrard, Lange, Riggenbach, Steinmeyer, against the supposition of a legend, resolve themselves into arbitrary assumptions and foreign importations which simply leave the matter as historically incomprehensible as ever. The same thing may be said with regard to the emendation which Olshausen takes the liberty of introducing, according to which it is made to appear that the Sanhedrim did not act in their corporate capacity, but that the affair was managed simply on the authority of Caiaphas alone. Still the unhistorical character of the story by no means justifies the assumption of an interpolation (in opposition to Stroth in Eichhorn’s ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Repert",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". IX. p. 141),—an interpolation, too, that would have had to be introduced into three different passages (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 27:62",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 27:66",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 28:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 28:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ff.); yet one can understand how this apocryphal story should have most readily engrafted itself specially and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "exclusively",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " upon the Gospel of Matthew, a Gospel originating in Judaeo-Christian circles, and having, by this time, the more developed form in which it has come down to us. For a further amplification of the legend, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ev. Nicod",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". 14.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 27:65",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἔχετε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": probably imperative, not indicative = have your watch, the ready assent of a man who thinks there is not likely to be much need for it, but has no objections to gratify their wish in a small matter. So most recent interpreters—Meyer, Weiss, Holtz., Weizsäcker, Morison, Spk., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Com.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Alford. The Vulgate takes it as indicative = ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "habetis",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which Schanz follows. This rendering implies that Pilate wished them to be content with what they had already, either their own temple watch or soldiers already put at their disposal. Carr (Camb. N. T.) doubts the correctness of the modern interpretation on the ground that no clear example of the use of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἔχειν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in the sense of “to take” occurs in either classical or Hellenistic Greek.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κουστωδίαν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a guard, a Latinism, a natural word for the Roman Pilate to use.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὑπάγετε ἀσφαλίσασθε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the three verbs: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἔχ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὑπάγ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀσφαλ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "., following each other without connecting particles form an asyndeton “indicating impatience on the part of Pilate” (Camb. N. T.).—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὡς οἴδατε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as ye know how.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "65",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ye have a watch",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The meaning is either (1) that Pilate refuses the request; “Ye have a watch of your own”—(",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") the Levitical temple guard, or (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "b",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") a small body of soldiers whom Pilate may have already placed at their disposal—or (2) he grants it curtly and angrily, “Take a watch; begone.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The latter view is generally adopted now. It seems quite clear from ch. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 28:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that the guard was of Roman soldiers.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
